@node "description" Description...  
Description  
===========  
  
With this package it is possible to use a PC Network card with your Amiga.
You only need an Commodore Bridgeboard (A2088, A2286 or A2386) which transports
the hole packet traffic from to/from the ISA PC Network card.

The Device is SANA2/R2 compatible, so that the  
network cards can be used with the most Amiga TCP-Stacks (Miami, AmiTCP...).
Now it's possible to use cheap PC network cards for your Amiga...
  
The software consists of an @{B}Amiga Sana2 Device@{UB} for the Amiga side and
a small @{B}PC Server Program @{UB} for the PC side of the bridgeboard.  
The PC server communicates over a @{B}MSDOS Device Driver@{UB} with the network card.  
The two sides (Amiga and the PC) exchange their data with help of the  
Janus-Software over the Dual-Ported-Ram of the bridgeboard. @{SW-Schichten link "layer.iff/MAIN"}
The Amiga-Device has the possibility to start the PC-Server and package driver
automatically on the PC side.
  
The @{B}Packet Driver@{UB} must be a PCTCP compatible DOS driver. These comes along with
the most PC Network cards. If you have no driver look at "@{B}ftp.ftp.com@{UB}".
I have include drivers for a @{B}NE2000@{UB} and a @{B}3com509@{UB} in this archive.
  
  
The archive consists of the following files:  
  
@{B}etherbridge.device@{UB}: Amiga  SANA2/R2 compatible device driver
@{B}EBSERVER.EXE@{UB}      : PC servers on the bridgeboard side
@{B}NE2000.COM@{UB}        : PC network card driver for a NE2000
@{B}3C509.COM@{UB}         : PC network card drivers for a 3Com509
@{B}EtherPrefs@{UB}        : MUI Preferences program for etherbridge



@endnode  
  

@node "requirements" Requirements...  
Requirements:
=============  
  
 - Amiga-OS >= V2.0  
  
 - a Commodore Bridgeboard A2088, A2286 or A2386   
  
 - PC network card with a PCTCP compatible PC driver
  
 - Janus.library V36 (Janus2.1)  
  
 - Amiga network software (AmiTCP, Miami, Genesis, ...)  
  
 - MUI 3.8 (only for configuration with EtherPrefs)  
  
@endnode  
  
  
  
  
  
  
@node "installation" Installation...  
Installation  
============  
  
The installation is simple:  
  
Please copy:  
  
@{B}etherbridge.device@{UB} => "@{B}devs:networks/@{UB}"
@{B}etherbridge.config@{UB} => "@{B}env:sana2/@{UB}" and "@{B}envarc:sana2/@{UB}"
@{B}EBSERVER.EXE@{UB}       => "@{B}c:\...@{UB}" (somewhere on the bridgeboard (PC side))
@{B}EtherPrefs@{UB}         => "@{B}sys:Prefs@{UB}"
a package-driver   => "@{B}c:\...@{UB}" (somewhere on the bridgeboard (PC side))
  
  
To configure the Device please use the program @{B}EtherPrefs@{UB}.
It supports the following attributes:
  
  
@{B}DOS Driver@{UB}:  
   Please select here the used MSDOS packet driver.  
   With a mouse click on @{B}Edit@{UB} you can edit the driver properties.
   It open a window with the following fields:
  
         @{B}Alias Name@{UB}:  
            This is a name for the driver (for example "My NE2000").
  
         @{B}Driver@{UB}:  
            Please type here the path and filename of the DOS driver.  
            This is an MSDOS path! Don't forget to use backslash!  
            (for example "c:\program\ebserver.exe").
  
  
         @{B}Parameter@{UB}:  
            The exact command line of the packet driver. Mostly an  
            NE2000 has the following syntax:  
  
               "0x60 <Interrupt No.> <IO-Base>"
  
            For example my NE2000 needs the parameter "0x60 4 0x320". This means:
            Soft interrupt 0x60, network card interrupt 4 and IO address of 0x320,
  
            Please read the manual of your network card to get the right parameter.  
              
  
  
@{B}PCSERVER@{UB}:  
   This is the path and name of the PC Servers on the bridgeboard in (MS)DOS  
   notation (for example "c:\dos\ebserver.exe"). Don't forget
   the file extension (".exe")!!!!
  
  
@{B}Mode@{UB}:  
   Communication mode to the PC side. Since the bridgeboard  
   A2088 and A2286 has speed problems with the interrupt signaling  
   the etherbridge device provide the following modes:  
  
         @{B}A2386@{UB}:  
            This use interrupts for the communication. The fastest mode on an A2386 but
            also on some systems of A2088 and A2286. Please try it out!   
              
  
         @{B}A2088/A2286@{UB}:  
            Only for the A2088/A2286. This use a mix of  
            Interrupt and polling functions for the communication.   
            This method is typically faster with these bridgeboards but not on all systems.
            You have to try it out!
              
               
               
  
@{B}Transmit Buffer@{UB}:
   Number of the used transfer buffers to the bridgeboard  
   Normally this should be 2.  
  
@{B}Device Task Pri@{UB}:
   Task priority of the Device Task. Should be 0.  
  
@{B}Packet Tracer@{UB}:
   Packet protocol function. It's possible to log all in and out going packets
   to a file or console.
  
@{B}Tracefile@{UB}:
   filename or Consolename in which the output should be written.
  
  
You can test your Network card on the side @{B}Interface Test@{UB}.  
Press "Start" Button to send some packets on the wire and press "Stop" for stopping this test.
  
  
  
  
  
Using with AmiTCP  
==================  
  
If you want to use the Device with AmiTCP the file  
"@{B}AmiTCP:db/interfaces@{UB} " must contains the following line:  
  
  
----cut----  
  
@{B}etherbridge DEV=DEVS:Networks/etherbridge.device UNIT=0@{UB}  
  
----cut----  
  
Now you can reach the Device with "etherbridge".
(for example: Shell> online etherbridge)
More information about the configuration of devices can be taken from the documentation of AmiTCP.  


  
  
  
  
Using with Miami  
================

If you use Miami I have included my config file from Miami3.2  
in "@{B}Miami/My.config@{UB}".

@endnode
  
  
  
@node "properties" "Properties of the Etherbridge.device"
Propoerties of the Etherbridge.device  
====================================  
  
- SANA2 Release 2 compatible  
- supports the @{B}"New Style Device"@{UB} command (NSD)
- start the server on PC side automatically if needed  
- packet protocol function to log in and out going packets  
    
  
  
  
Perfomance  
==========  
  
So far, I have done better experiences with the speed of AmiTCP as of Miami.
Unfortunately packetes sometimes get lost with Miami (ringbuffer overflow)!
Generally, Miami seems to be slower!
  
Here are some few transfer-values (approximately):
  
                              Amiga Amiga  
TCP/IP-Stack | protocol | send       | receives | answer-time      |
--------------------------------------------------------------------  
AmiTCP 4.0d  | ftp      | 335KB/s    | 226KB/s  |                  |
             | Samba    | 160KB/s    | 209KB/s  |                  |
             | ping     |   ---      |   ---    |    3/4ms         |
-------------------------------------------------------------------|  
Miami3.2     | ftp      | 190 KB/ses | 240KB/s  |                  |
             | Samba    | 133 KB/ses | 166KB/s  |                  |
             | ping     |   --       |  --      |    5/6ms         |
-------------------------------------------------------------------|  
  
These values refer to following installation:  
  
  
AMIGA4000: CybPPC604 with MC68040/25MHz, 80MB Fast-RAMs,  
A2386: 8MB-RAM, 20MHz, NE2000, A2386_PS2-Ram-Adapter  
PC: K6/2 300MHz, 64MB-Ram, NE2000-Netzwerkkarte, Windows95  
  
  
  
  
Something about the A2286/A2088:
================================
  
Don't expect to much speed with these cards! My old Amiga 2000 (MC68000)
with an A2286 bridgeboard and a 3com509 network card reaches
about 40-50 kbs!!!! With another processor this may be a little bit more...

If you want to use the A2088 you must get an PC packet driver which
supports 8 bit to the network card (because of the XT-Bus).
The included NE2000 driver doesn´t seem to support this but the driver for
the 3COM works fine in 8 bit mode.
Possible there are other NE2000 driver which support 8 bit mode. Please
have a look at "ftp.ftp.com" to get new PCTCP drivers...
  
     
  
  
  
  
This things are not yet implementated:
======================================
  
 - SANA2R2/R3 Multicasts  
  
 - SANA2R2 Packet Tracking  
  
 - Raw Packets  
  
 - Even more speed...  
  
 - Extension of EtherPrefs:  
     - Performance tests  
     - Display Device and PCTCP driver properties
  
 - perhaps an Install-Script  
  
@endnode  
  
  
@node "history" History  
  
 @{B}History@{UB}
 ==========  
 
 V1.2.2   (29th Oct. 2013)
   - Bugfix: Still a problem with A2088 Bridgeboard. Now it's working.
   - Bugfix: Interrupt mode (COMMODE=0 in Prefs) was not working correctly.
     COMMODE=1 (polling) was used instead.
   - Some code cleanups on DOS Server (the Amiga Device is currently not changed)

  
 V1.2.1   (13th Jul. 2013)
   - Bugfix: EBServer.exe is now able to run on A2088 (a file was compiled 
     with 386 option and can't run on an 8088)
   - Update contact data


 V1.2   (6th Jul. 1999)
   - config keys changed
   - configuration program "EtherPrefs" added
   - speed optimizations
   - bug removed in buffermanagement handling
   - finished the english manual


 V1.1   (18th Dec. 1998) (not published)
   - some speed improvments
   - Using Janus lowlevel functions for more speed instead of
     janus service functions
   - more time for a character transmit (Starting DOS Server)
   - support of DOS drivers ("PCTCP" compatible)
   - remove some little bugs
   - support of device flag "PROMISC"
   - rework of the DOS server "EBSERVER.EXE"
   - support for A2088 and A2286
   - startup busy window


 V1.01  (16th Aug. 1998)
   - added an default config file "etherbridge.config"


 V1.0   (10th Aug. 1998)
   - first public release


 V0.1   (22th May 1997)
   - start developing
     
@endnode  
  
  
  
